I like this challenge. It is easy to understand, and has good level of difficulty for a clash of code.

I wrote the JavaScript snippet below to solve it.

My only question to you is regarding the tests/validators. You have put a lot of them, but it is not obvious to me how they differ from each other. 
For example, is there a reason to have a test for 77 [test 8] if we already have a test for 33 [test 7]?
Don't get me wrong, some  have clear value (eg 121: prime squared, or 36: prime product squared, etc...), but I am not sure about some that look similar.
A test for the number 2 would have been good to have though (first prime and also first value in our range).

-----------------------------------
My JavaScript solution
-----------------------------------

const n = parseInt(readline());

const isPrime = n => {
    for (let i = 2; i < n/2 + 1; i++) {
        if (n % i === 0) return false;
    }
    return n > 1;
}

const isPrimeProduct = n => {
    for (let i = 2; i < n/2 + 1; i++) {
        if (n % i === 0) return isPrime(n/i);
    }
    return false;
}

console.log(isPrimeProduct(n));

I solve it with this Python program:
n = int(input())

primes = [2]
for potential in range(3, n + 1, 2):
    is_prime = True
    for prime in primes:
        if potential % prime == 0:
            is_prime = False
            break
    if is_prime:
        primes.append(potential)

is_product_prime = False
for prime in primes:
    if n % prime == 0:
        if n // prime in primes:
            is_product_prime = True
            break

print(str(is_product_prime).lower())
